issue.body:
Just noticed with https://github.com/babel/babel/issues/7350, we're making a bunch of very long string arrays. What's more, they're (mostly) duplicated between the `strings` and `raw`.

```js
tag`some template`;
// "some template" "some template"
_taggedTemplateLiteral(["some template"], ["some template"]);
```

The only (I think) time that string arrays aren't duplicated is when an "invalid" escape sequence comes up (which are now valid, due to template literal revision).

```js
tag`test${1}\xhello`;
// "invalid" string becomes undefined
_taggedTemplateLiteral(["test", void 0], ["test", "\\xhello"]);
```

At worst, we could optimize the "all valid strings" case using slice:

```js
// default raw value to a slice of strings
function _taggedTemplateLiteral(strings, raw = strings.slice()) {
  return Object.freeze(Object.defineProperties(strings, {
    raw: { value: Object.freeze(raw) }
  }));
}

// all valid
tag`some template`;
_taggedTemplateLiteral(["some template"]);

// some invalid
tag`\xhello`;
// "invalid" string becomes undefined
_taggedTemplateLiteral([void 0], ["\\xhello"]);
```

But, realistically, we could just reuse the same string array (it's being frozen, anyways):

```js
function _taggedTemplateLiteral(strings, raw) {
  return Object.freeze(Object.defineProperties(strings, {
    raw: { value: raw ? Object.freeze(raw) : strings }
  }));
}
```

