We have a related issue here with HTML Imports https://github.com/Polymer/polymer-cli/issues/950 and a need to fix it on the Babel side in the best case.

I do understand that this is likely not Babel's responsibility to deal with such edge cases, but at the same time I ask myself: are there many cases where caching of a template literal is really helpful? Also TypeScript compiler doesn't cache and calls a helper creating a template object directly in place like this:

```
function _taggedTemplateLiteral(strings, raw) { return Object.freeze(Object.defineProperties(strings, { raw: { value: Object.freeze(raw) } })); }

var tag = function tag(v) {
  return v;
};

(function () {
  tag(_taggedTemplateLiteral(["some template"], ["some template"]));
})();
```

My draft implementation for Babel 6 doing similar stuff https://github.com/babel/babel/compare/6.x...bashmish:template-literals-in-html-imports?expand=1

I can make a proper MR with fixed tests and also do the same for Babel 7, **fixing this issue as a side effect** as well.

Is there any chance to reconsider this optimisation strategy and take my (ok, TypeScript's) approach instead?

Learned a lot about the underlying spec and now see how naive my previous comment was, sorry guys :D just started exploring the rationale behind transpilers implementations.

Also looked in depth at how TypeScripts implements it. Interesting read here https://github.com/Microsoft/TypeScript/wiki/What's-new-in-TypeScript#cache-tagged-template-objects-in-modules

The most confusing part is how TypeScript compiles the same code without `export`.

```
// original example for TS 2.6 changelog

export function id(x: TemplateStringsArray) {
    return x;
}

export function templateObjectFactory() {
    return id`hello world`;
}

console.log(templateObjectFactory() === templateObjectFactory()); // true in TS 2.6
```

```
// without module exports 

function id(x: TemplateStringsArray) {
    return x;
}

function templateObjectFactory() {
    return id`hello world`;
}

console.log(templateObjectFactory() === templateObjectFactory()); // still false in TS 2.6
```

I'm still trying to grasp the spec and if it somehow implicitly dictates this difference in TS behavior (or it's just a bug there), especially latest changes mentioned in the issue description https://github.com/tc39/ecma262/pull/890

Sorry, the context has sort of been lost. I just wanted to explain why we do things the way we do.

There was a comment above from @bashmish about why it's werid that TypeScript doesn't cache the template object when a file isn't a module (i.e. when you don't have imports or exports in a module). I was mainly responding to that.

The reason is that in a module, you can always ensure you have a unique variable that won't collide with anything else for a template object, but in the global scope, you're susceptible to collisions. So we kept the no-caching behavior to avoid name clashes

```ts
(function () {
  tag(__makeTemplateObject(["some template"], ["some template"]));
})();
```

as opposed to the behavior you might encounter in a module:

```ts
var _a;
(function() {
    tag(_a || (_a = __makeTemplateObject(["some template"], ["some template"])));
})();
```

I was explaining our eventual strategy for dealing with name clashes in the global scope. We were thinking of using our `makeTemplateObject` function as a map to have an easy way to reference these objects, but maybe generating a very long global identifier that's sufficiently distinguished by its contents would be good enough.

This would actually give you the old spec-compliant behavior in the global scope, with the new spec-compliant behavior in modules. I think that's good enough for most use-cases.

> I was explaining our eventual strategy for dealing with name clashes in the global scope. We were thinking of using our makeTemplateObject function as a map to have an easy way to reference these objects

Careful, that'll lead to very easy memory leaks. Now any template literal in scope will cause all template literals in scope to remain in memory, even if the callsites are long GC'd.

```js
(function() {
    tag(__makeTemplateObject._a || (__makeTemplateObject._a = __makeTemplateObject(["some template"], ["some template"])));
})();

window.someExport = function() {
  return tag(__makeTemplateObject._b || (__makeTemplateObject._b = __makeTemplateObject(["long lived template"], ["long lived template"])));
};
```

Here, `_a` template will never be cleaned up (as long as `someExport` is alive).
